    <name>
      <text>8.1.24 (Geom. seq. choose salary)</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Claire is applying for a new job. She receives two job offers.<p>
<br/>
<p>Offer A : £\({@starta@}\) to start followed by a guaranteed annual increase of \({@rate1a@}\) for the first \(10\) years.</p>
<br/>
<p>Offer B : £\({@startb@}\) to start followed by a guaranteed annual increase of \({@rate1b@}\) for the first \(10\) years.</p>
<br/>
<p>What is the salary of Claire in year \({@nn@}\) with each job offer?</p>
<p>Offer A: [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</p>
<p>Offer B:  [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>We form a geometric sequence that governs Claire's salary for both offers.</p>
<br/> 
<p>Offer A:</p>
<p>In this case the first term is {@starta@} and because we are told that her salary increases by a rate of {@rate1a@}, the common ratio is \({@rate2a@}\) we can use the general formula for a geometric sequence as follows:
\[
u_n = ar^{n-1} = {@starta@} \cdot {@rate2a@}^{n-1}.
\]
We need to find Claire's salary after \(n\) years so we require \(u_{@nn@}\) which is
\[
u_{@nn@} = {@starta@} \cdot {@rate2a@}^{{@nn@}-1} = {@finsala@}
\]
Hence after {@nn@} years her salary with this offer is £{@ta1@}.</p>
<br/>
<p>Offer B:</p>
<p>Similarly, the first term is {@startb@} and because we are told that her salary increases by a rate of {@rate1b@}, the common ratio is \({@rate2b@}\). Thus we can use the general formula for a geometric sequence as follows:
\[
u_n = ar^{n-1} = {@startb@} \cdot {@rate2b@}^{n-1}.
\]
We need to find Claire's salary after \(n\) years so we require \(u_{@nn@}\) which is
\[
u_{@nn@} = {@startb@} \cdot {@rate2b@}^{{@nn@}-1} = {@finsalb@}
\]
Hence after {@nn@} years her salary with this offer is £{@ta2@}.</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
